name: No.100 - Matlock

name: No.189 - Phoebe
notes: Absolute Bastard to pick. Key pin in is a magentic gin.  Chambers 3-5 are HB famous piston pins (ball in chain inside) while chamber 6 has a key pin that is pin in pin.

name: No.190 - Dolphins
notes: Absolute Bastard to pick. Chamber 1 driver is a screw type pin in pin with a spring in spring.  Chamber 2 driver is ball/chain/piston pin.  Chamber 4 driver is a rattlesnake.  Chamber 5 driver is a magnet gin with a magnetic key pin.   Plug mods with threading and extra undercuts.  In the bible, 1-4 threaded and can't tell he did that from the top side.

name: No.191 - Telesto
notes: Even the bible was threaded for three chambers.  Threaded/undercut plug.  Pin in pin, Piston Pin and spools.

name: No.198 - Copper Pig
notes: This was a bastard.  Couldn't get tension to float.  Used BOK with a fat Moki tensioner (HB drilled the face of the keyway to make it tougher).  Threaded chambers and piston pins.  6th one was almost a no lift.

name: No.199 - Copper Pig Babby

name: Bite X
notes: Another baster to get open.  Because of the milling and serrated/gin/tree pins, it is very hard to distiguish a set pin.  Picked it CW.  Jam the high lifts up.  So 5 & 6, the 1 & 3.  Then lift the lower lifts 2 and 4.  Then revisit the high lifts until it's open.  No finesse in this pick.

name: P.I.T.A.
notes: Definitely a PITA.  All key pins were standards.  The plug was milled with trench traps on both sides of each chamber hole to all ow for rounded t-pins to slip into.  A floating wafer sat on each t-pin.  If the stack is lifted to the correct height, the sheer line for each stack would be between the key pin and the wafer.  If any of the 6 t-pins slips into a trench trap, the lock will not open.  It was common to get a 50 degree swing from 90 degrees for both CW and CCW.
